\caption{\footnotesize {\bf a)}
 The amplitude ${\mathcal A}$ represents a $CP$-violating contribution
to a hypothetical process $X^0\rightarrow{\pi^{+}}$. Differences in the $X^0\rightarrow{\pi^{+}\pi^{-}}$ and $\bar{X}^0\rightarrow{\pi^{+}\pi^{-}}$ decay rates
can only be observed if it interferes with a $CP$-conserving process (amplitude = ${\mathcal C}$) that has
a non-zero common phase $\phi_0$.  
{\bf b)}  Excerpts from page 1 (above) and page 12 (below) of the classic Kobayashi-Maskawa paper~\cite{km73}. 
